  "prompt": "What's the size of a 4K image?",
  "response": "A 4K image typically refers to an image with a resolution of 3840 x 2160 pixels, which is known as Ultra High Definition (UHD). The size of a 4K image in terms of file size can vary greatly depending on several factors, including:\n\n1. **Color Depth**: The number of bits used to represent each pixel (e.g., 8-bit, 10-bit).\n2. **Image Format**: Different formats (JPEG, PNG, TIFF, etc.) use different compression methods.\n3. **Compression Level**: Lossy compression (like JPEG) reduces file size more than lossless compression (like PNG or TIFF).\n\nAs a rough estimate:\n- A basic uncompressed 4K image with 24 bits per pixel (8 bits for each RGB channel) would be approximately:\n  \n  \\[\n  3840 \\, \\text{pixels} \\times 2160 \\, \\text{pixels} \\times 3 \\, \\text{bytes/pixel} = 24,576,000 \\, \\text{bytes}\n  \\]\n\n  This equals about 24.6 MB.\n\n- For compressed formats (like JPEG), the file size can be significantly less, often between 1 MB to 5 MB, depending on the quality settings used during compression.\n\nIt's important to consider the specific context and usage to get a more precise file size.",
